Author: msn <msn@polaris.dev>
Date:   Wed Jun 10 17:20:22 2026 -0700

    I-perm-004 (#1198) slice 2: wire span_resolver argmax into the cited re-anchor path (PG_SPAN_RESOLVER)
    
    Default OFF -> byte-identical (first-passing loop unchanged). When PG_SPAN_RESOLVER is truthy, the
    cited re-anchor (Path 1 of `_try_reanchor`) chooses the BEST entailing prose span via the
    boilerplate-aware argmax instead of the FIRST passing candidate in enumeration order — the drb_76
    "re-anchored to the row TITLE" bug.
    
    Safety: the resolver's judge IS the existing full gate — a closure that re-binds the [#ev] token to
    the candidate span and runs `verify_sentence_provenance(allow_local_window_fallback=False)`. So the
    argmax can only ever choose among spans that ALREADY pass the exact same content+numeric+entailment
    bar; it never lowers the bar. A title-only-supported claim is still recovered but the soft-warning
    carries `q=<provenance_quality>:c=<confidence>` so the report ships it caveated, never silently high.
    Judge calls bounded by PG_SPAN_RESOLVE_TOPK (default 4). New telemetry `reanchor_argmax_recovered`.
    
    Also folds the slice-1 iter-2 residual P2 (compact `home|articles|archive` link bars without spaces
    around pipes now classify as nav_link) and refines the resolver `judge_fn` signature to
    `(sentence, span, span_text)` so the wiring closure can re-bind by offsets.
    
    Behavioral proof (offline, fake judge): a row where the supporting clause appears in BOTH a
    Title-Case segment (enumerated first) and a later prose segment — flag OFF binds the title
    (`reanchored:`), flag ON binds the prose span (`reanchored_argmax:...:q=prose`) and they are
    DIFFERENT spans. OFF byte-identity preserved (the 13 existing reanchor tests + the telemetry-contract
    test pass with the new key=0 in OFF mode).
    
    Tests: 14 reanchor (incl. the argmax behavioral + OFF byte-identity) + 9 span_resolver = 23 green.
    
    Next slice: wire the resolver into the gap-#18 ACCEPT path (re-point the token on a local-window
    rescue instead of passing on the original mis-pointed span) + the uncited Path 2; then #1180 widening.
    
    Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>

